 Despite the unequal and sometimes fraught relations between Blacks and Jews in the Caribbean before and after emancipation, Black-Jewish literary encounters reflect sympathy and identification more than antagonism and competition. Providing an alternative to U.S.-based critical narratives of Black-Jewish relations, Casteel reads Derek Walcott, Maryse Condé, Michelle Cliff, Jamaica Kincaid, Caryl Phillips, David Dabydeen, and Paul Gilroy, among others, to reveal a distinctive interdiasporic literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCaribbean literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aCaribbean literature (French)xHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewszCaribbean AreaxIdentity. 7aPOETRY / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aChancy, Myriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCliff, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondé, Maryse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDabydeen, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHearne, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKincaid, Jamaica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaillet, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilip, M. Nourbese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Caryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPissarro, Derek Walcott’S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/cast1744040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231540575423Coveruhttps://www.